<p>Some time ago, my mother attended college night at my school. While she sat inside listening to college counselors\' lectures, I was outside enjoying my "freedom."  However, this wasn\'t such a good idea - on the way home, my mom started a conversation that\'s still stuck in my head.</p>
<p>"You need busy summers," she said. I mistook this for a random statement.</p>
<p>"Uh, why?" (Yes, I\'m oh-so-witty.)</p>
<p>"Because colleges want kids who have busy summers and you already have had one slacker summer," my mother explained.</p>
<p>I was stunned. Attending an expensive private school, maintaining a respectable GPA, and participating actively in clubs and sports weren\'t enough; nope, I had to have "busy summers" as well.</p>
<p>It\'s true that the Silicon Valley (along with the rest of the world) has become more competitive; we have many excellent private and public schools filled with students who have above average intelligence. But somehow it seems wrong that in order to get ahead of these kids in the race for college, I have to sacrifice my summer as well.</p>
<p>What is a busy summer? According to my teachers and parents, a summer is only busy if you are working, interning, taking classes, or volunteering. Sadly, traveling isn\'t on that list.</p>
<p>When all this had been explained to me, I came to the brilliant conclude that I had had a busy summer. Pleased, I informed my mother that I had gone to the NJCL convention.</p>
